--- variable ----------------------------------------------------------

Variable is naming but name given to the block of memory.
A variable in JavaScript is a named container used to store data. The value stored in a variable can change while the program runs.
We can create a variable in javascript using declaration types.

-- Syntax--
variable_declaration_type  variable_name = value;
ex: 
let age = 20;

Declaration type :--
 There are three types of declaration 
i. var  ii. let  iii. const

i. var :--
            var is traditional way to declare the variables.
            It can be redeclared and update the value within the scope.
            It Can be reassigned and declare without initialization also it can be accessed before declaration and its returns undefined.
            Function-scoped.
            Older way (before ES6).

example : var city = "Mumbai";
          console.log(city);

          city = "Pune"; // Reassigned
          console.log(city);

          var city = "Delhi"; // Redeclared
          console.log(city);

ii. let :--
            Cannot be redeclared in the same scope.
            Can be reassigned.
            Block-scoped.
            Recommended for variables whose value may change.

example : let age = 22;
          console.log(age);

          age = 23; // Reassigned
          console.log(age);

          // let age = 24; // ❌ Error: Cannot redeclare

iii . const :---
                  Cannot be redeclared.
                  Cannot be reassigned.
                  Block-scoped.
                  Use it for values that should not change.

example : 
            const PI = 3.14159;
            console.log(PI);
            // PI = 3.14; // ❌ Error: Assignment to constant variable
                
